		<header>
			
			<h1>FSC receive assurances over sale of Tate &amp; Lyle sugar division</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, Fijian Permanent Secretary for Sugar Manasa Vaniqi received assurances at a briefing in London in mid July that the sale of Tate &amp; Lyle’s European Sugar assets to American Sugar Refining (ASR) would carry no implications for existing contractual arrangements previously agreed between Tate &amp; Lyle and the Fiji Sugar Corporation (FSC). The current long-term agreement provides the framework for the delivery of up to 300,000 tonnes of raw sugar per annum to Tate &amp; Lyle for the period up to 30 September 2015. Tate &amp; Lyle have also given assurance that ‘their commitment to the implementation of the Fair Trade Initiative at sugar mills’ across Fiji will be unaffected.</p><p>At the meeting, Permanent Secretary Manasa Vaniqi briefed Tate &amp; Lyle managers on government efforts to revive the sugar sector. Recent measures taken include: the financial restructuring of the FSC; the implementation of cost-cutting measures; the launching of a F$150 million investment programme; and land reform measures to boost sugar cane planting. However, these measures need to be seen against the backdrop of an 11.1% decline in FSC’s turnover, the loss of around F$30 million in the 2009 season, a decline of nearly 10% in raw sugar exports to the UK, and a cane throughput of around 50% of installed milling capacity.</p><p>According to analysis by the Dean of Business and Economics of the University of the South Pacific, the low rate of cane conversion to sugar attained by FSC could lead to losses equivalent to $100 million in the coming season. Before 1990 FSC used 8-9 tonnes of sugar to produce 1 tonne of raw sugar, and sucrose extraction rates have been declining ever since, with some 13.6 tonnes of sugar cane currently needed to produce 1 tonne of raw sugar (although factory performance varies from 13.1 tonnes of cane per tonne of sugar to 26 tonnes per tonne of sugar).</p><p>In March 2010 this situation saw Fiji halt regional exports of sugar and place restrictions on local purchases, to prevent sugar exports to neighbouring Pacific islands as part of consolidated consignments. These actions were taken to maximise supplies of sugar to fulfil long-term contractual obligations on the EU market. According to press reports, ‘FSC produced a total of 167,611 tonnes of sugar during the 2009 season.’</p>
		
		
