				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The recent exchange of assurances between FSC and managers of the Tate &amp; Lyle sugar division over the future of long-term supply arrangements which pre-date the signing of the first Lomé Convention, need to be seen in the context of the long-term decline in both Fijian sugar cane production and sucrose extraction rates, and the possible reorientation of supply relationships which the sale of Tate and Lyle’s sugar division to ASR could bring about in the long term. </p><p>It is now a matter of urgency for FSC to improve both cane quality and milling efficiency in order to take cane production and sucrose extraction rates back towards previously prevailing levels which were more in line with international competitiveness needs. This can be seen as essential if ongoing supply problems are not to lead to a suspension of the existing contract for breach of supply obligations.</p><p>In this context, the ongoing land reform by the government has to offer effective security of tenure to the cane farmers without undermining the interests of the landowners. This requires careful conceptualisation and operationalisation of the proposed ‘land bank’, and the successful implementation of planned reforms of FSC itself to establish an efficient, lean, cost-effective modern corporate entity.</p><p>In the face of a likely decline in EU market prices, trends towards the globalisation of activities of EU sugar sector companies, and the more integrated approach to the exploitation of sugar cane being adopted by a large number of sugar producers (via the use of cane residues for electricity con-generation and molasses and lower-quality cane juice for ethanol and alcohol production), FSC may also need to rethink its existing long-term role as primarily an exporter of raw sugar. </p><p>Consideration will increasingly need to be given to the opening up of new revenue streams from electricity co-generation and ethanol production, and even the scope for increased value-added processing, not only involving greater refining of raw sugar but also exploring the scope for sugar-based chemical and pharmaceutical production. This in turn may require a strategic reappraisal of FSC’s relationship with Tate and Lyle’s former sugar division, which reaches beyond the current efforts to promote the production and marketing of fair-trade-certified sugar.</p>
		</div>
		
